node.text: Melissa Miranda (@meltronica) shares her version of a gin and tonic with @bombaysapphireus, taking inspiration from the Philippines with a riff on the Gin Pom. With grapefruit, ginger, cardamom bitters, a squeeze of lime, and @bombaysapphireus, this drink will remind you of being on the beach. #StirCreativity

node.text:
**Sound On** In honor of Mother’s Day, best-selling author and poet Kwame Alexander (@kwamealexander) asked 12 accomplished writers to reflect on how their lives—and their kitchens—mirror their mothers. Everyone got the same prompt, “I am becoming my mother,” and this community poem is a result. Head to the link in our bio to read more about the authors.
Contributors: @vanggarrett, Lesléa Newman, @engle.margarita, @marjorythw, Richard Michelson, Janet Wong, @georgiaheard1, @amstephens_, Maritza Rivera, Reuben Jackson, Lorna Goodison, @erikalsanchez, Deanna Nikaido, and Kwame Alexander

node.title: Kwame Alexander Reads The Ceremony of Giving

node.text: Chef Sheldon Simeon (@chefwonder) is an entrepreneurial guy, almost to a fault. Between doing a run on @bravotopchef’s 10th season, opening (and sometimes leaving) restaurants on Maui, and publishing his acclaimed cookbook Cook Real Hawai’i (cowritten with @g_sny). he’s always working on something. “I don’t think I’d be a chef if I didn’t grow up in Hawai’i,” Simeon told restaurants editor Elyse Inamine (@elysei). “As crazy as it sounds, aloha spirit is a real thing. It touches you. It makes you want to rep Hawai’i hard.” Read about how Simeon’s not just bringing attention to Hawai’i’s cuisine but redefining it, at the link in our bio. 📷: Kevin J. node.text: Green goddess dressing doubles as a marinade AND a sauce for these juicy grilled chicken thighs. Use whatever tender herb or dairy product you have, but whatever you do, don’t skip the anchovies! Senior food editor @ andybaraghani says, “They will make the chicken savory, delicious, and more chicken-y.” We believe him. node.text: When grilling a whole chicken, we stand by two tried-and-true methods: spatchcocking the bird so it cooks evenly and seasoning it with dry rub so you get flavor into every nook and cranny. This recipe from assistant food editor @thelescook checks those boxes, with a foolproof grilling method for the spatchcocked bird and an umami-packed dry rub (five-spice and MSG!). We’re making it all summer, and you should, too. Grab the recipe link in our bio. 📷: @emmafishman 🍴: @susietheodorou 🥣: @tripleppp

node.text: Making doughnuts at home is not only possible but fun! And these magnificent, cardamom-cream-filled doughnuts are a great place to start. Breaking cardamom pods in with the pastry cream ingredients will give all other doughnut fillings a run for their money. From getting the dough started to rolling the finished doughnuts in sugar, recipe developer @samanthaseneviratne breaks down the art of making doughnuts from start to finish. Grab the recipe link now in our bio. 📷: @isa.zapata 🍴: @curlygirlcooks 🥣: Nicole Louie

node.text: The key to these juicy grilled chicken breasts? Treating your grill like an oven and dousing the chicken with a tadka-ish sauce. For this recipe, @rachelgurjar blooms whole spices and scallions in oil to maximize their flavor and aroma, then drizzles it over cooled, sliced chicken and greens dressed in a lemony buttermilk dressing. This two-pronged method means perfectly grilled chicken breasts every time (you’re welcome!). Grab the recipe link in our bio. 📷: @emmafishman 🍴: @susietheodorou 🥣: @tripleppp

node.text: Dinuguan, the rich Filipino blood stew, has many names. But as a child in Toronto, contributor Yasmin Tayag often heard her relatives call it chocolate meat—a teasing moniker that unsettled her. “Perhaps they felt that jokes like ‘chocolate meat,’ which made light of the differences that made them unique, would ease their entry into a new society,” she writes of the Filipino immigrant experience. Her essay, which traces the dish’s origins from the colonial era all the way to her present, argues to reclaim the term “dinuguan” as a celebration of Philippine creativity, resourcefulness, and defiance. 🎨: @lydia_ortiz

node.text: We're calling it: Galatopita (ruffled milk pie) is the must-make summer dessert. This Greek treat calls for scrunching up layers of buttered phyllo, pouring a bath of custard over it, and baking it to crispy-creamy perfection. The end product tastes as dreamy as it looks. “This dessert has so many textural contrasts,” recipe developer @samsanthaeneviratne says, “with crunchy phyllo tops, juicy berries, and creamy custard. Fresh raspberries add a welcome tartness to all the sweetness in the mix.” Grab the recipe link now in our bio. 📷: @emmafishman 🍴: @susietheodorou 🥣: @tripleppp

node.text: Assistant food editor Jessie YuChen (@thelescook) developed a way to grill wings for a crowd that makes it more effortless and foolproof than ever. Baking the wings ahead of time means that there’s no fretting over the grill wondering whether they’re cooked through, and allows you to achieve caramelized perfection with minimal effort. You get an impressive looking dish, a fiery grill show, and easy-breezy-under-control hosting. Read more at the link in our bio. 📷: @emmafishman 🍴: @susietheodorou 🥣: @tripleppp

node.text: “The mouthwatering smell of pollo asado brings to mind so many memories of walking from my grandparents’ house to the neighborhood fritanga stand around the corner,” says chef Giovanna Favilli. Giovanna’s pollo asado recipe offers a taste of those childhood memories. A whole chicken gets marinated in a mix of punchy flavors like naranja agria (sour orange) juice and achiote paste. But no worries if you can’t get your hands on sour oranges—Giovanna recommends subbing a mix of orange and lime juice instead. Grab the full recipe in our bio now. 📷: @emmafishman 🍴: Rebecca Jurkevich
